    "recap_headline": "California State University Northridge Athletics",
    "recap_text": "NORTHRIDGE, Calif.\n---CSUN Baseball posted a 12-1 victory over Pepperdine in seven innings on Monday at Robert J. Hiegert Field. The Matadors used a five-run third and a seven-run fifth to produce their 12 runs. Five CSUN pitchers combined to limit the Waves to one run on six hits while racking up eight total strikeouts.\nEight of the nine Matador starters recorded at least one hit with both\nWill Linberg\nand\nColton Boardman\nproducing two hits.\nKyle Panganiban\nwould hit a grand slam in the victory.\nHOW IT HAPPENED\nThe Waves would push across the game's first run in the top of the third. After\nCharles Rogers\nworked two shutout innings and recorded the first out of the third, Pepperdine took advantage of two walks and a hit batsman with\nJackson Banuelos\non the mound to take a 1-0 lead. CSUN went to its bullpen once more with two outs and the bases loaded, bringing in\nAdam Christopher\n. The Northridge native\u00a0minimized the damage by getting the third out moments later, keeping the deficit at one run.\nCSUN would have a quick response in the home half of the third inning, batting around in a big five-run outburst. Following a\nVaughn Coleman\nleadoff walk, Linberg and\nAndrew Becker\neach doubled to tie the game at 1-1. Later in the frame,\nMatthew Thomas\nripped a triple to right center field to add to the lead while\nMatthew Pena\nlooped in a double down the left-field line to score another.\nJehee Lee\ncapped the scoring spree with an RBI single for a 5-1 Matador lead.\nThe Matadors' biggest inning though came in the fifth inning when another seven runs came across, all with two outs. Boardman extended the inning by drawing a walk before\nTrent Abel\ndoubled in two runs. A hit batter and two more walks set the stage for Panganiban who belted an 0-1 pitch over the left-center field fence for a grand slam and a 12-1 lead.\nOn the pitching side, Christopher tossed back-to-back shutout innings after the third, including stranding runners at the corners in the top of the fifth. Freshmen\nGage McCown\nand\nJack Jones\neach worked an inning to close the game out, scattering a pair of hits between them.\nNOTES OF THE GAME\nCSUN improves to 10-6 on the season while Pepperdine slips to 3-12.\nChristopher was credited with the victory, the\u00a0first of his Matador career, after tossing 2.1 innings and striking out three batters while allowing three hits and no runs.\nRogers, who started for the second straight day, worked 2.1 innings and struck out three batters with just a run allowed.\nPanganiban has reached base safely in seven straight games.\nThomas has now posted six multi-RBI games to lead the team.\nACCORDING TO COACH EDDIE CORNEJO\n\"I was really happy with the way we pitched. We had two really good stops by\nAdam Christopher\n, a local Northridge guy who is pitching his heart out in his last season. A good job of passing the baton by our bullpen throughout the game.\n\"Our offense needs to get better because it keeps sputtering at the start of the game, first time through the order and they need to get better at being more in attack mode. We'll work on that but overall, we did a good job.\"\nUP NEXT\nCSUN returns to Big West play this weekend with a three-game series against UC San Diego at Robert J. Hiegert Field. The opener is set for Friday at 5 p.m.\n#GoMatadors"
  },
